  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he marvelled that he had not first washed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Literally, “",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "bathed.” ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "No washing was necessary to eat a few dates or figs. At the chief meal of the day, where all dipped their hands into a common dish, it was a matter of cleanliness. But the duty of cleanliness had been turned by the Oral Law into a rigorous set of cumbersome and needless ablutions, each performed with certain elaborate methods and gesticulations (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 7:2-3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") which had nothing to do with religion or even with the Levitical Law, but only with Pharisaic tradition and the Oral Law. In the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Shulchan Aruk,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " a book of Jewish Ritual, no less than twenty-six prayers are given with which their washings are accompanied. But all this was not only devoid of divine sanction, but had become superstitious, tyrannous, and futile. The Pharisee ‘marvelled’ because he and his party tried to enforce the Oral Law on the people as even more sacred than the Written Law. The subject of ablutions was one which caused several of these disputes with Christ, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 15:19-20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Rabbi Akhibha would have preferred to die of thirst rather than neglect his ablutions, and the Talmud thought that a demon—called Schibta— sat on unwashen hands. Our Lord astonished the conventionalism of these religious teachers and their followers by shewing that what truly defiles a man is that which cometh ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "from within",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—from the heart.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
